item.title: Shipping containers wash on to NSW beach
item.description: Five 40-foot shipping containers from a Singapore-flagged vessel that lost part of its load have washed up on a NSW beach.

item.title: Premiers must explain border closures: PM
item.description: Scott Morrison has challenged the Liberal premiers in Tasmania and South Australia to justify keeping their borders closed, as Pauline Hanson threatened to take the Queensland government to court.

item.title: Hong Kong anthem bill spurs protests
item.description: Hong Kong police have fired pepper pellets and made arrests in the city's central business district as protests sprung up in multiple districts in response to the likely passing of a bill that criminalises "insulting" China's national anthem.

item.title: Missing Kiwi bushwalkers found alive
item.description: Two young bushwalkers missing in New Zealand's Kahurangi National Park for 18 days have been found alive.

item.title: Construction fell again in March quarter
item.description: Construction work fell less than expected in the three months to March, suggesting the decline in GDP for the quarter may not be as much as economists have previously forecast.

item.title: Japara expects $300m virus hit to goodwill
item.description: Japara Healthcare has flagged a hefty non-cash impairment charge of $270 million to $300 million, mostly against goodwill, in its full-year financial results as a result of the coronavirus crisis.

item.title: Chimp lip smacks clue to human speech
item.description: Lip smacks made by chimpanzees follow a rhythm similar to human speech, according to a new study.

item.title: Vic education manager redirected $14m
item.description: A former education department project manager misused his position to direct almost $14 million worth of contracts to his own IT company, the Victorian corruption watchdog has found.

item.title: Get your frothies: SA pubs get ready to go
item.description: South Australians are getting ready to enjoy their first 'frothies' in front bars with the easing of coronavirus restrictions, prompting a leading local brewer to ramp up keg production.

item.title: Calls to stop jailing Australian children
item.description: Children as young as 10 continue to be locked up in Australia, with policy-makers urged to unite on raising the age of criminal responsibility at an upcoming meeting.
